<BaseLayout title="Teaching" description="Agreni Batra's teaching philosophy, courses, and current roles.">
  <div class="max-w-2xl mx-auto px-6 py-14">
    <h1 class="text-3xl font-serif font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-6">Teaching</h1>

    <!-- Teaching philosophy -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-serif font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-4">Teaching Philosophy</h2>

      <!-- PLACEHOLDER: Replace with real teaching philosophy before launch -->
      <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        I approach teaching as a practice of co-inquiry. My role as an instructor is not to
        transmit a fixed body of knowledge but to create conditions under which students can
        develop as disciplinary thinkers — people who ask generative questions, sit productively
        with uncertainty, and revise their thinking in response to evidence and the ideas of
        others. This requires careful attention to the design of tasks, the norms of classroom
        discourse, and the relational texture of the learning community.
      </p>
      <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        I hold the conviction that rigor and access are not in tension. The highest intellectual
        expectations, paired with genuine relational support and carefully scaffolded entry points,
        produce the deepest learning. Lowering expectations in the name of "meeting students where
        they are" is not kindness — it is a failure of belief. What meeting students where they
        are actually requires is a detailed understanding of what they already know and can do,
        and an instructional design that builds from that foundation rather than ignoring it.
      </p>
      <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
        My teaching has been shaped significantly by work in contexts where students carry
        significant stress from outside the classroom and where instructional time is a scarce
        resource. These constraints have made me a more precise and intentional designer of
        learning experiences, and more attuned to the difference between activities that feel
        engaging and activities that produce genuine conceptual development.
      </p>
    </section>

